item.title: EU Talks on Economic Recovery Aid to Enter Third Day
item.description: Major differences remained on the amount of grants that would be handed out to struggling national governments as part of an economic recovery fund.

item.title: Canada Bars Blue Jays From Playing Home Games in Toronto
item.description: Canada won’t allow the Blue Jays to play Major League Baseball games in Toronto this season, citing the risk posed by team players and staff traveling to parts of the U.S. where the risk of Covid-19 transmission is elevated.

item.title: French Officials Investigate Arson After Fire Burns Through Nantes Cathedral
item.description: French authorities opened an investigation into arson after a fire broke out Saturday in a cathedral in the western city of Nantes. The blaze prompted comparisons to the one that engulfed Notre Dame Cathedral in Paris last year.

item.title: Tens of Thousands March in Russia's Far East, Defying Kremlin
item.description: Tens of thousands of people in Russia’s Far East marched in protests triggered by the arrest of a popular regional governor, but that have since morphed into a wave of growing dissatisfaction over social issues and the rule of President Vladimir Putin.

item.title: Travel Is Bouncing Back, but Tourists Stick Close to Home
item.description: In many parts of the world, travelers are out and about again. But they are staying largely in their own countries, driving a welcomed rebound in tourism as few have the ability to venture off to faraway destinations.

item.title: Saudi Arabia Wants Its Fugitive Spymaster Back
item.description: Officials say billions in a Saudi counterterrorism fund under the control of spy chief Saad al Jabri have gone missing. Jabri’s supporters say the money was used to fight terrorists and the system was approved by the former crown prince. Western officials are worried an investigation could expose secrets.
